05550nam a22009255i 9781400826780DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2009    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008267807 a10.1515/97814008267802doi  a(DE-B1597)446507  a(OCoLC)979744901  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aHV17 .C65 2008 7aHIS0370102bisacsh04a362.5/089/9240621 aCohen, Mark R., eauthor.10aPoverty and Charity in the Jewish Community of Medieval Egypt /cMark R. Cohen.  aCourse Book 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2009] 4cÂ©2006  a1 online resource :b2 halftones.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aJews, Christians, and Muslims from the Ancient to the Modern World ;v3000t Frontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. A Taxonomy of the Poor -- tChapter 2. The Foreign Poor -- tChapter 3. Captives, Refugees, and Proselytes -- tChapter 4. Debt and the Poll Tax -- tChapter 5. Women and Poverty -- tChapter 6. "Naked and Starving," the Sick and Disabled -- tChapter 7. Beggars or Petitioners? -- tChapter 8. Charity -- tChapter 9. Conclusion: Poverty and Charity, Continuity and Acculturation -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Geniza Texts -- tGeneral Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat was it like to be poor in the Middle Ages? In the past, the answer to this question came only from institutions and individuals who gave relief to the less fortunate. This book, by one of the top scholars in the field, is the first comprehensive book to study poverty in a premodern Jewish community--from the viewpoint of both the poor and those who provided for them. Mark Cohen mines the richest body of documents available on the matter: the papers of the Cairo Geniza. These documents, located in the Geniza, a hidden chamber for discarded papers situated in a medieval synagogue in Old Cairo, were preserved largely unharmed for more than nine centuries due to an ancient custom in Judaism that prohibited the destruction of pages of sacred writing. Based on these papers, the book provides abundant testimony about how one large and important medieval Jewish community dealt with the constant presence of poverty in its midst. Building on S. D. Goitein's Mediterranean Society and inspired also by research on poverty and charity in medieval and early modern Europe, it provides a clear window onto the daily lives of the poor. It also illuminates private charity, a subject that has long been elusive to the medieval historian. In addition, Cohen's work functions as a detailed case study of an important phenomenon in human history. Cohen concludes that the relatively narrow gap between the poor and rich, and the precariousness of wealth in general, combined to make charity "one of the major agglutinates of Jewish associational life" during the medieval period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aCairo Genizah. 0aIslamxRelationsxJudaism. 0aJews |z EgyptxCharitiesxHistory. 0aJewszEgyptxCharitiesxHistory. 0aJewszEgyptxSocial conditions. 0aJudaismxCharitiesxHistory. 0aJudaismxRelationsxIslam. 0aPoorzEgyptxHistory. 0aPovertyxReligious aspectsxJudaism. 0aSocial sciences. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066258008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton Univ. Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311041343408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311045953140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400826780423Coveruhttps